node.title: DBS Formulation
node.bodyText:
Check these boxes if you have followed the posting rules.

 Q&A Navier Stokes is the most appropriate category for my question
 I have consulted the posting Guidelines on the Discussions front page
 I have searched the Discussions forum and my question has not been asked before
 I have searched the MOOSE website and the documentation does not answer my question
 I have formatted my post following the posting guidelines (avoid screenshots if possible, triple back quotes before/after pasted text, etc)

Question
Dear MOOSE Contributors @cpgr
I'm seeking guidance and assistance in developing a MOOSE program (DBSFLOW) tailored for simulating reactive transport at the micro-continuum scale, specifically using the Darcy Brinkman formulation.
My objective is to model the complex interplay of fluid flow and reactive transport phenomena within porous media, focusing on the intricate details at the microscale. My proposed program would used more of the kernel developed in Navier Stoke and PorousFlow Modules with certain modification. The The Darcy Brinkman formulation is a sig=ngle pressure field equation that couple Navier stoke and Darcy into one equation. In the matrix the the reduces to darcy, as you go from porous region to solid region such as in vugs or fracture,  the equation asymptotically reduces to Navier stoke flow.
I have attached below a figure of my proposed media, and research paper of this implementation in OPENFOAM.  II like to replicate this in MOOSE with improvement to capture slightly compressible flow that is applicable to CO2 storage in fractured-vuggy carbonate reservoir. I believe that MOOSE's capabilities are well-suited for this task, particularly with its flexibility and robustness in handling multiphysics problems.
Multiphase flow modeling in multiscale porous media.pdf


Any specific guidance on how to implement the Darcy Brinkman formulation within the MOOSE framework? Additionally, I would appreciate any insights or best practices that could streamline the development process and ensure accurate simulation results.

Hello
The three equations can be implemented in moose. Would the variables be velocity, phi and pressure?
Once you have identified the variables, you should decide which discretization to use. Both modules have a continuous galerkin finite element and a finite volume implementation that can serve as examples.
The paper mentions two flow regimes can be present, Darcy and NS flow. Do you plan to have the same equation over the entire domain and the flow regime naturally lets some terms be important and others be negligible ?
We have tutorials on creating new applications here:
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/examples_and_tutorials/index.html
Chris will have more targeted advice
Guillaume

node.title: How to generate 1/4 Cylinder and apply symmetry boundary conditions
node.bodyText:
[Mesh]
  [base]
    type = AnnularMeshGenerator
    dmax = 90
    nr = 4
    nt = 5
    rmin = 0
    rmax = 4
  []
  [gauge]
    type = MeshExtruderGenerator
    extrusion_vector = '0 0 10'
    bottom_sideset = 'bottom'
    top_sideset = 'top'
    num_layers = 10
    input = base
  []
  [./left]
    type = BoundingBoxNodeSetGenerator
    new_boundary = left
    bottom_left = '0 0 0'
    top_right = '0 -4 10'
    input = gauge
  [../]
[]

In order to generate 1/4 Cylinder and apply symmetry boundary conditions, I must add 2 new boundaries surface left and back. But how can the boundary "left" created by this mesh be a straight line instead of a surface? (I also tried top_right(0,4,10), it is still a line, then I am totally confused).
Peacock always leads to segment fault, so I used Paraview to see the mesh.

Hello
Use this generator instead for extruding
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/meshgenerators/AdvancedExtruderGenerator.html
It will turn the 1D lines sidesets in the 2D mesh into 2D surface sidesets in the 3D mesh
Otherwise you can easily regenerate such surfaces using a ParsedGenerateSideset

node.title: Object not registered even though it exists
node.bodyText:
Check these boxes if you have followed the posting rules.

 Q&A General is the most appropriate section for my question
 I have consulted the posting Guidelines on the Discussions front page
 I have searched the Discussions forum and my question has not been asked before
 I have searched the MOOSE website and the documentation does not answer my question
 I have formatted my post following the posting guidelines (screenshots as a last resort, triple back quotes around pasted text)

Question
I have a kernel called DiffusionCoupled. It is a custom kernel that I added to my application. I have both the .h and the .C files in their appropriate folder, include/kernels and src/kernels within the application (called difluoride). I have used this kernel in the past for previous applications, and everything seems to work fine when I use it in that application (called xenon). I then ported an exact copy of the kernel to the new app difluoride. I remember to change the name of the application within the .C kernel to re-register it to the new application.
All this being done, I tried to run the application and I got the following error:
hwloc/linux: Ignoring PCI device with non-16bit domain.
Pass --enable-32bits-pci-domain to configure to support such devices
(warning: it would break the library ABI, don't enable unless really needed).
*** ERROR ***
A 'DiffusionCoupled' is not a registered object.
We loaded objects from the following libraries and still couldn't find your object:
libphase_field-opt.la
If you are trying to find this object in a dynamically loaded library, make sure that
the library can be found either in your "Problem/library_path" parameter or in the
MOOSE_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable.
Stack frames: 22

5: MooseObjectAction::MooseObjectAction(InputParameters const&)
6: AddKernelAction::AddKernelAction(InputParameters const&)

8: ActionFactory::create(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator > const&, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator > const&, InputParameters&)
9: Moose::Builder::walkRaw(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator >, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator >, hit::Node*)
10: Moose::Builder::walk(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator > const&, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits, std::allocator > const&, hit::Node*)

17: ./difluoride-opt(+0x30eb) [0x55fde79500eb]

20: __libc_start_main
21: ./difluoride-opt(+0x3396) [0x55fde7950396]
application called MPI_Abort(MPI_COMM_WORLD, 1) - process 0
I tried renaming the files and application, but I didn't see any changes. Any help would be appreciated. I can provide the kernel and input file if that would be needed.

Hello

I remember to change the name of the application within the .C kernel to re-register it to the new application.
All this being done, I tried to run the application and I got the following error:


what did you register it to?
did you remember to recompile the opt executable in between?
Guillaume
try MooseApp instead of 'difluorideApp'
i Just did and I get the exact same error message. I did try changing the name previously, to something like DiffusionCoupledCustom to see if that ould work and also changing the name of the .h.

the file must not be compiled then
where is it in the app?

I retired it today, and changing it to MooseApp seems to register it; I might have either forgotten to save the changes or recompiled it last time in my haste. I am getting a different error now (for which I think I have the solution), so let me make sure it runs, and then I will mark it as the answer.
What is the difference between registering with " difluorideApp " and " MooseApp "? I used the previous registration scheme on previous projects, "xenonApp," and the kernels seemed to work fine there.
The difference is that MooseApp always works, whereas if you got a single letter wrong in " difluorideApp" or if it should be " DifluorideApp" instead, then it wont work
Thank you very much. I assume a recommended practice is to write all custom kernels to MooseApp unless it is hyperspecific to the application?
In your application, you should register the kernels to your application. But if for any reason it does not work, registering to MooseApp does not hurt anyone

node.title: Error for missing required parameter
node.bodyText:
Check these boxes if you have followed the posting rules.

 I have consulted the Posting Guidelines.
 I have searched the Discussions Forum and MOOSE Framework Troubleshooting and have not found what I was looking for
 Q&A Getting Started is the most appropriate category for my question (trouble installing, beginner user, ...)

Issue or question about MOOSE
Dear moose users,
I try to compile input files from:  https://github.com/hugary1995/eel
There is one error I got when I run the input file:
missing required parameter 'Materials/chemical_energy/reference_chemical_potential'
Doc String: "reference chemical potential"
The parameter was defined as:
EntropicChemicalEnergyDensity::validParams()
{
  InputParameters params = ChemicalEnergyDensity::validParams();
  params.addRequiredParam<Real>("ideal_gas_constant", "The ideal gas constant");
  params.addRequiredCoupledVar("temperature", "The temperature");
  params.addRequiredCoupledVar(
      "reference_concentration",
      "The reference concentration at which the entropic chemical energy density is zero");
  params.addRequiredParam<MaterialPropertyName>("reference_chemical_potential",
                                                "reference chemical potential");
  return params;
}

so it means that this parameter should be used in the input file as it is required as defined, but in the inputfile it is not mentioned, that's why I got the error, right?
  [chemical_energy]
    type = EntropicChemicalEnergyDensity
    chemical_energy_density = psi_c
    concentration = c
    ideal_gas_constant = ${R}
    temperature = T
    reference_concentration = c_ref
  []

How can I change it to make the simulation run? just try to run this, no need to think about the physics behind.
Thank you for your help in advance.
Best regards,
Xiao
(Optional) code in question / simulation log / errors
No response
Encountering Errors? Please include diagnostic output
No response

I added mu_ref for required parameter <reference_chemical_potential>
first defined it in auxVariables and then initialize it as below:
[mu_ref_min]
type = ConstantIC
variable = mu_ref
value = 0
block = 'anode'
[]
[mu_ref_mid]
type = ConstantIC
variable = mu_ref
value = 0
block = 'elyte'
[]
[mu_ref_max]
type = ConstantIC
variable = mu_ref
value = 0
block ='cathode'
[]
I got error like:
Material property 'mu_ref', requested by 'chemical_energy' is not defined on block anode
Material property 'mu_ref', requested by 'chemical_energy' is not defined on block elyte
Material property 'mu_ref', requested by 'chemical_energy' is not defined on block cathode

Hello

so it means that this parameter should be used in the input file as it is required as defined, but in the inputfile it is not mentioned, that's why I got the error, right?

yes you need to specify this parameter.
For mu_ref, you are getting an error because the chemical_energy requested a material property, and seemingly you added a variable for mu_ref instead
yes, thank you, I added the property in the material block, and the error is gone.

node.title: Error in making and testing moose
node.bodyText:
I have been trying to compile and test moose onto my windows machine using WSL. I have followed the steps provided at https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/installation/conda.html under getting started. I went all through cloning MOOse and every step seemed to work however when it comes to building and testing moose I keep getting the same error (see below).
Error in question:

Compiling C++ (in opt mode) /home/ambroisej/projects/moose/test/build/unity_src/dgkernels_Unity.C...
{standard input}: Assembler messages:
{standard input}: Error: open CFI at the end of file; missing .cfi_endproc directive
{standard input}:457952: Error: invalid operands (*UND* and .gcc_except_table._ZN31PostprocessorInterfaceErrorTest11validParamsEv sections) for `-'
x86_64-conda-linux-gnu-c++: fatal error: Killed signal terminated program cc1plus
compilation terminated.
make: *** [/home/ambroisej/projects/moose/framework/build.mk:150: /home/ambroisej/projects/moose/test/build/unity_src/userobjects_Unity.x86_64-conda-linux-gnu.opt.lo] Error 1
make: *** Waiting for unfinished jobs....

I copied and pasted the commands provided under that section however when running make -j 6 it will compile for a couple of minutes before returning the error shown above. The first time I ran this my laptop died so I initially just reran it while restarting from the top however the error persisted. I also assumed it could be from lack of space on my disk however I have around 120Gb of free memory left so I am not sure.
any help would be appreciated, thanks.

Hello
Can you try make -j 1 ?
Kill signals often happen when you run out of memory. and -j6 will use quite a bit
Guillaume
It was indeed simply this. I thought I had tried, but I guess not. In any case, thank you very much for the help; it is appreciated.
Appreciate the insight. I ran into the same error and resolved it through make -j 3
